President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring May 2016 as National Building Safety Month. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of maintaining safe and resilient structures in our buildings, and recognizes the individuals and organizations that work to ensure building safety. The proclamation highlights the use of disaster-resistant building codes and materials, as well as safe design methods, to protect against natural disasters. It also mentions the Federal Government's efforts to strengthen the security and resilience of federal buildings, and the upcoming Conference on Resilient Building Codes. The proclamation stresses the need for buildings to be resilient to the impacts of climate change, and emphasizes the importance of energy efficiency in building design. President Obama calls on citizens, government agencies, businesses, and nonprofits to raise awareness about building safety and to take action to safeguard America's homes, schools, and other buildings.